label chapter10:

    # [Scene: Beacon Lighthouse | Late Afternoon — Several Months After the Seawall Construction]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano, low and resonant; a single cello undercurrent]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind carrying the distant rasp of machinery; fewer gull calls, a hollow echo where chorus used to be]
    "You stand on the rocky outcrop beneath the lighthouse and let the wind wash the salt into your hair. The seawall is a clean, unforgiving seam — a promise kept for roofs and jobs, a line"
    "that does not bend for tides. It hums with the memory of machines that never slept: the diesel taste beneath the fog, the hollow thrum of engines moving bulk and concrete, the metallic clink of anchors"
    "being set into rock."
    "Your fingers find the sea-glass pendant at your throat because you do not know where else to rest them. It is cool and honest against your skin; it does not answer. You listen instead for what"
    "has changed — the way the shore smells sharper now, like steeped brine instead of peat and reed; the way the boardwalks creak with a different weight because there is less life under the water to"
    "soften footprints."
    "Noah Rhee comes up the path with rope coiled over his shoulder, boots carrying the darker, permanent smell of work. He moves like someone who has settled an old account and keeps checking the till."
    show noah_rhee at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_rhee "You ought to be easy on yourself, Maya."
    "He leans against the railing, eyes following the seawall."
    "You watch his jaw work. He smells of tar and storm, of coffee brewed too long in a flask. For a long moment you simply watch him, counting the lines the years at sea have carved around his eyes."
    show maya_ibarra at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "You saved a lot, Noah. But we traded a lot, too."
    "Your voice is quieter than you expect. 'The marsh is shrinking. The sensor logs—juvenile counts are down, salinity's creeping inland. The nets come back lighter.'"
    "Noah Rhee's face is unreadable for a second — and then the old fierceness reappears, less theatrical now, sharpened by long days. He holds your gaze like a plank, steady."

    noah_rhee "We did what we had to. If the town floods, there are no nets to talk about. You know that."
    "He spits into the wind, an old ritual of defiance. 'Don't make it sound like I wanted marshes gone.'"

    maya_ibarra "I know you didn't want that."
    "You hear your own impatience. 'But you pushed for speed and guarantees. You convinced people who were tired and hungry. Now some of them won’t listen to anything that sounds like 'long-term.''"
    "Noah Rhee's voice loses volume, becomes almost a confession."

    noah_rhee "I watched my father freeze on a boat once. I promised him I wouldn't let his kids drown in his harbor."
    "He looks away, at the seawall. 'If that costs birds, I can't sleep at night, but I can sleep with my family dry. Maybe you can't forgive me for that.'"

    maya_ibarra "I'm not trying to punish you."
    "You reach out before you can second-guess the gesture. Your hand hovers as if offering a bridge. 'I'm trying to understand how we became a place that treats habitat like a ledger.'"
    "Noah Rhee's jaw loosened, then tightened. He nods once, brief and brittle."

    noah_rhee "Understand it all you want. But when the nets are empty and people are angry, talking won't fill bellies."

    menu:
        "Step closer and say nothing":
            "You close the distance and let the silence do the work. Noah's shoulders drop a fraction, and for a breath you share a quiet that remembers working together on docks, not breaking apart over blueprints."
        "Tell him he chose the wrong thing":
            "You let the accusation fall, sharp as a knife. Noah flinches, anger flickers back into his eyes, and the space between you hardens as if carved by winter wind. He answers with a fury that contains exhaustion."

    # --- merge ---
    "..."
    "Noah doesn't stay long. He turns, the rope swinging, and the harbor takes him back into its rhythm. You remain on the rocks until the lamp blinks again, counting the light as if it were a metronome for your decisions."
    # [Scene: Port Veridian — Council Hall | Midday — A Public Briefing]
    hide noah_rhee
    hide maya_ibarra

    scene bg ch9_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet strings; a slow, descending motif]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Murmurs, the rustle of paper, a child's intermittent cry]
    "Mayor Cortez stands at the podium with a stack of printed summaries. Her expression is that of someone who has learned to keep hope thin and practical. Beside her, an Aria Sol-type representative from Veridian Holdings — poised, immaculate — watches the room as though stage-managing the weather."

    "Mayor Cortez" "We've secured the town's flood insurance thresholds and steady employment over the winter months."
    "She taps the podium. 'That was not easy.'"

    "Aria (Veridian Holdings)" "Our phased approach succeeded in stabilizing load-bearing soils and immediate tidal threat."
    "She smiles, practiced. 'The region watches Port Veridian as a model for scaling protection.'"
    "You present the monitoring packets you brought — the repeated charts, the sediment maps, the juvenile fish counts pinned in red. Your voice trembles in the beginning and steadies as you go on. You are both advocate and mourner."
    show maya_ibarra at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "The seawall is doing what it was engineered to do. But the data shows cascading impacts: salinity intrusion inland by measurable margins, nursery habitats losing structure, shorebirds abandoning traditional sites. This is not hypothetical; it's happening now."
    "Drifts of cold air fall between statements like leaves. A man in the back claps once, slow, for the jobs. A younger woman near the front shakes her head at the red lines on your charts."

    "Mayor Cortez" "We balanced lives and livelihoods. I took a lot of calls. I had to choose the option that would keep electricity on and food on tables while we secure longer-term grants."

    maya_ibarra "And what will we do when the longer-term grants fail to materialize?"
    "The question scrapes across the atrium. 'Who tends the marsh? Who pays for adaptive governance when the immediate money dries up?'"

    "Aria (Veridian Holdings)" "Adaptive governance is part of our proposal's second phase. We can negotiate monitoring timelines."
    "Her tone remains smooth. 'The economic multiplier of secured ports and industries will provide funding.'"

    maya_ibarra "We have declining juvenile counts now. If the multiplier assumes biological recovery that isn't happening, what then? No one modeled that scenario into the funding schedule."
    "Mayor Cortez breathes out, the weight of leadership making the air thin."

    "Mayor Cortez" "We made a trade. We will need to manage the consequences as best we can."
    "There is no applause for that line. Only the low murmur that follows such truths."

    menu:
        "Push the council to commit to a strict, independent monitoring board":
            "You lay out procedural language for oversight, eyes on Mayor Cortez. There is nodding, bureaucratic friction — promising words that may or may not change the reality on the ground."
        "Hold back and let the town breathe — don't push now":
            "You let the moment pass, choosing not to force the wound open. The room shifts toward smaller comforts: coffee, handshakes, a temporary truce that tastes like salt and paper."

    # --- merge ---
    "..."
    "You leave the hall with your charts damp from the drizzle that has started again. The town swallows the briefing like a tide — some parts drawn in, some left behind."
    # [Scene: Harbor Wharf | Dawn — The Morning Elliot Leaves]
    hide maya_ibarra

    scene bg ch9_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A solitary violin, keening gently]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Small, intimate — a kettle boiling on a distant deck, the muted cry of an early gull]
    show elliot_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "They offered me a fellowship to study coastal interventions in diverse contexts. A chance to look at what works, and what didn't, from a distance."
    "He avoids looking at the seawall directly. 'It’s... an opportunity.'"
    show maya_ibarra at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "You were the one who argued for a hybrid, for nuance."
    "You press your thumb against the sea-glass pendant. 'Why leave just when the model needs people here to defend it?'"
    "Elliot Chen: [a small, sad smile] 'Because sometimes you have to step away to see whether what you built actually scales without being co-opted.'"
    "He meets your eyes. 'And because I keep getting pulled toward projects where the trade-offs are framed in metrics I can't stand by without checking them myself. This fellowship is to learn how to make designs that hold up against people like Aria as well as people like Noah.'"

    maya_ibarra "So you think you can make it better from a distance."

    elliot_chen "I don't know. I hope so."
    "He takes a breath. 'Maya, you taught me how important place-based knowledge is. Leaving won't make me forget that.'"
    "Elliot Chen reaches for your hand. The contact is brief and deliberate; a human attempt to tether the future."

    elliot_chen "We could try—long-distance, collaboration, something."
    "He swallows. 'But I understand if you can't—if Port Veridian needs you.'"

    maya_ibarra "It needs me in ways I can't always be. I know that."
    "Your voice breaks and you cough it away. 'If you go, promise me one thing: don't let their reports sanitize the costs. Don't let the charts tell a prettier story than the shoreline.'"

    elliot_chen "I promise."
    "He releases your hand, turns his suitcase toward the waiting vehicle. 'I'll write. I'll try to make useful trouble.'"
    "He gives you a look like someone folding a map he doesn't want to lose. Then he walks away, shoulders square, leaving you with the hollow step of someone leaving a room after a long meeting."

    menu:
        "Call after him and ask him to stay":
            "You open your mouth and the words scramble. He pauses, then shakes his head gently. The plea would only trap him, and you know it. He moves on with a small, grateful nod."
        "Let him go, and fold the goodbye into the work ahead":
            "You watch him leave. You let the goodbye be what it is: a release and a bruise. The tasks ahead sharpen in your chest."

    # --- merge ---
    "..."
    "The harbor swallows his figure. The sky opens a little more, like a bruise being exposed to air."
    # [Scene: Montage | Months That Follow]
    hide elliot_chen
    hide maya_ibarra

    scene bg ch9_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, elegiac piano with occasional wind chimes]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant machinery, a single bird call fading into static]
    "You watch the data accumulate like a ledger that does not add up in anyone's favor. Juvenile fish counts dip season after season. Salinity sensors show salt moving inland in small, relentless increments. Nesting counts drop;"
    "species shift where they nest, if they nest at all. A handful of workers get stable contracts. Some fisheries revise quotas downward. A few small businesses that had depended on the ebb of tourists and fish"
    "shutter. The town's payrolls are steadier, but the old seasonal rhythms are gone."
    "Neighbors you used to trade eggs with now avoid your eye at the market, not because you are blamed outright, but because you are a reminder of a decision that changed the way the town breathes."
    "There are quiet conversations that begin with, 'We needed something,' and end with silence about what was given away."
    "Noah Rhee is elected to a new committee overseeing harbor operations. He keeps his distance from social gatherings; the applause for his leadership is sometimes thin, sometimes exuberant. Pride and isolation live together in his shoulders."
    "Elliot Chen's postcards come in bursts, full of maps and questions. He writes about new methods and old mistakes; he sends a photograph once of a successful hybrid trial in another town and remarks that context"
    "matters in ways that can't be exported. You answer sometimes, with long, careful notes about soil, about people, about the things that numbers do not capture. Your correspondence is an attempt to stitch a network; it"
    "is not always enough to mend what was worn."
    # [Scene: Shoreline Beneath the Seawall | Dusk — Your Departure]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A slow, resigned cello line; a distant soprano wind]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft clack of a suitcase latch, the whisper of the sea, one close gull call]
    "You close the satchel and test its weight. Inside are the printed reports you could not let go of, a notebook full of marginalia, the smartwatch with tide logs, a small roll of photographs — Rosa's"
    "work that both indicts and comforts. Your sea-glass pendant rests warm against your palm before you loop it over your head."
    "You walk the path you walked as a child, the one that used to have drier reedbeds to hide in, the one that now has a thin crust of salt where the water crept closer. The"
    "town behind you is awake with lights and small sound: the hum of a freezer, the muttered voices from a late shift, the clatter of a café stirring for a night crew. It is ordinary and"
    "precious in the same beat."
    "At the small pier, Noah Rhee is there — not an overseer now, but a man who has kept his oath to his family. He does not offer an embrace, but he holds out a pocketknife, a simple truce tied into a leather thong."
    show noah_rhee at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_rhee "Keep it."
    "He manages a small, lopsided smile. 'If you ever come back for a night, cut a rope with it and let me know you made it through.'"
    show maya_ibarra at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "I'll come back."
    "You say it because you mean it in the sense of a tide that always remembers its bed. 'Not always in the same way.'"

    noah_rhee "That's all anyone can promise."
    "He turns away first, the harbor taking him like a familiar song."
    "You step into the waiting vehicle that will take you to the station and then to a regional office where they want you to help design governance for coastal adaptation across a broader span — a"
    "place where policies might outlast a single town's impatience. You do it because you believe the work will matter. You do it because staying feels, in some nights now, like consent to costs you cannot carry"
    "forever."
    "You walk a little way and then look back, at the seawall etching the horizon into a hard line. For a moment you imagine the marsh you wanted — a ribbed living dike of willows and"
    "woven coir, communities mending with the rhythm of seasons. That image is a small, private thing. It is also a wound."

    "Maya Ibarra (inward, steady)" "I will make what I can of this. I will carry witness."
    "You touch the pendant one last time, and let it rest. The lighthouse lamp swings once, then twice, pulsing amber into the dusk."
    hide noah_rhee
    hide maya_ibarra

    scene bg ch9_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Cello fades to a single sustained note and then silence]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The wind, soft; the faint click of the car door closing]
    "You do not close the chapter on Port Veridian with triumph. There are protections that hold roofs and bellies. There are scars in the mud and loss in the sound of birds that no longer sing"
    "where they used to. People survived; ecosystems were compromised. Trust has been fractured into pieces that will take years, maybe generations, to collect."
    "You carry the burden and the knowledge of what was done and what might be done differently elsewhere. That is the cost and the work that will follow you through the years. It is, in its own way, both failure and truth."

    scene bg ch9_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Final, low piano chord; a small wind chime fades]

    scene bg ch9_3be532_8 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
